04999nam a22008175i 9780231504454DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2012    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315044547 a10.7312/gasp157802doi  a(DE-B1597)458880  a(OCoLC)979909803  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aP85.S18 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a410.92  aER 5602rvk1 aGasparov, Boris, eauthor.10aBeyond Pure Reason :bFerdinand de Saussure's Philosophy of Language and Its Early Romantic Antecedents /cBoris Gasparov. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLeonard Hastings Schoff Lectures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Saussure, "Saussurism," and "Saussurology" -- tPART 1. Voluble Silence: Saussure and His Legacy -- tPART 2. Postulates About Language and Their Demise -- tPART 3. Language in Discourse -- tConclusion: Freedom and Mystery-the Peripathetic Nature of Language -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Swiss linguist Ferdinand de Saussure (1857-1913) revolutionized the study of language, signs, and discourse in the twentieth century. He successfully reconstructed the proto-Indo-European vowel system, advanced a conception of language as a system of arbitrary signs made meaningful through kinetic interrelationships, and developed a theory of the anagram so profound it gave rise to poststructural literary criticism.The roots of these disparate, even contradictory achievements lie in the thought of Early German Romanticism, which Saussure consulted for its insight into the nature of meaning and discourse. Conducting the first comprehensive analysis of Saussure's intellectual heritage, Boris Gasparov links Sassurean notions of cognition, language, and history to early Romantic theories of cognition and the transmission of cultural memory. In particular, several fundamental categories of Saussure's philosophy of language, such as the differential nature of language, the mutability and immutability of semiotic values, and the duality of the signifier and the signified, are rooted in early Romantic theories of "progressive" cognition and child cognitive development. Consulting a wealth of sources only recently made available, Gasparov casts the seeming contradictions and paradoxes of Saussure's work as a genuine tension between the desire to bring linguistics and semiotics in line with modernist epistemology on the one hand, and Jena Romantics' awareness of language's dynamism and its transcendence of the boundaries of categorical reasoning on the other. Advancing a radical new understanding of Saussure, Gasparov reveals aspects of the intellectual's work previously overlooked by both his followers and his postmodern critics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aLinguisticsxHistory. 0aLinguisticsxPhilosophy. 0aSemiotics. 0aStructural linguisticsxHistory. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/gasp15780423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231504454.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEB